<a class="definition-word" data-category="general-biology" id="primer">Primer</a> - A short, single-stranded <a href="#dna_desoxyribonucleic_acid">DNA</a> used in <a href="#dna_desoxyribonucleic_acid">DNA</a> replication. A primer binds a region of single-stranded <a href="#dna_desoxyribonucleic_acid">DNA</a> to form a primer-template complex which allows <a href="#dna_polymerase">DNA polymerase</a> to synthesise the complementary strand (primer extension). Since most <a href="#polymerase">DNA polymerases</a> are only able to catalyse the addition of a <a href="#nucleotide">nucleotide</a> to the <a href="#3_prime_end_3">3'</a> end of a <a href="#dna_desoxyribonucleic_acid">DNA</a> strand, primers are necessary for <a href="#elongation">elongation</a>. Primers are a necessary reagent for <a href="#polymerase_chain_reaction_pcr">PCR</a>.